hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Effective acceleration in the rotating frame at latitude $\lambda$ has a true‐gravity part $-g_{0}\,\mathbf e_{r}$ plus a centrifugal part $\omega^{2}R\cos\lambda\,\mathbf e_{\rho}$.  In the meridional $(r,\theta)$ plane one shows  
$$\mathbf e_{\rho}=\cos\lambda\,\mathbf e_{r}-\sin\lambda\,\mathbf e_{\theta},$$  
so  
$$\vec g_{\rm eff}
=-\,g_{0}\,\mathbf e_{r}
+\omega^{2}R\cos\lambda\bigl(\cos\lambda\,\mathbf e_{r}-\sin\lambda\,\mathbf e_{\theta}\bigr)
=\bigl(-g_{0}+\omega^{2}R\cos^{2}\lambda\bigr)\mathbf e_{r}
-\,\omega^{2}R\cos\lambda\sin\lambda\,\mathbf e_{\theta}.$$

2. The deflection angle $\alpha$ between $\vec g_{\rm eff}$ and the radial direction satisfies  
$$\tan\alpha
=\frac{\text{tangential component}}{\text{radial component}}
=\frac{\omega^{2}R\cos\lambda\sin\lambda}{\,g_{0}-\omega^{2}R\cos^{2}\lambda}\,. $$

3. Introduce $\epsilon=\omega^{2}R/g_{0}$ so that  
$$\tan\alpha=\frac{\epsilon\cos\lambda\sin\lambda}{1-\epsilon\cos^{2}\lambda}\,. $$  
Maximizing $\alpha$ is equivalent to maximizing $\tan\alpha$.  Define  
$f(\lambda)=\frac{\epsilon\sin\lambda\cos\lambda}{1-\epsilon\cos^{2}\lambda}$,  
and set $df/d\lambda=0$.  One finds after algebra  
$$\cos2\lambda=\frac{\epsilon}{2-\epsilon}.$$  
Hence  
$$\sin^{2}\lambda_{\max}
=\frac{1-\cos2\lambda}{2}
=\frac{1-\frac{\epsilon}{2-\epsilon}}{2}
=\frac{1-\epsilon}{2-\epsilon}\,. $$
